				<text>1.2.4.2 Simplify indices</text>
		</name>
    <questiontext format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<p class="HELM_exercise">Exercise <br></p>
<p>Use the laws of indices to simplify.</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
<li>\(\dfrac{a^{@a1@} \times a^{@a2@}}{a^{@a3@}}= \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]</li>
<li>\(\dfrac{m^{@b1@} \times m^{@b2@}}{m^{@b3@}}=\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]</li>
</ol>]]></text>
		</questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="moodle_auto_format">
				<text><![CDATA[<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>Use the first law of indices to simplify the numerator: </li>
    <p>\(\dfrac{a^{@a1@} \times a^{@a2@}}{a^{@a3@}}= \dfrac{a^{{@a1@}+{@a2@}}}{a^{@a3@}}= \dfrac{a^{{@a1+a2@}}}{a^{@a3@}}.\)</p>
    <p>Now use the second law to simplify the result:</p>
    <p>\(\dfrac{a^{{@a1+a2@}}}{a^{@a3@}}= a^{{@a1+a2@}-{@a3@}} = a^{@a4@}.\)<br><br></p>
    <li>Use the first law of indices to simplify the numerator: </li>
    <p>\(\dfrac{m^{@b1@} \times m^{@b2@}}{m^{@b3@}}= \dfrac{m^{{@b1@}+{@b2@}}}{m^{@b3@}}= \dfrac{m^{{@b1+b2@}}}{m^{@b3@}}.\)</p>
    <p>Now use the second law to simplify the result:</p>
    <p>\(\dfrac{m^{{@b1+b2@}}}{m^{@b3@}}= m^{{@b1+b2@}-{@b3@}} = m^{@b4@}.\)<br><br></p>
</ol>]]></text>
		</generalfeedback>
